[src:rosetta-code/100-doors-p01] There are 100 doors in a row that are all initially closed.
[src:rosetta-code/100-doors-p01] The first time through, visit every door and *toggle* the door (if the door is closed, open it; if it is open, close it).
[src:rosetta-code/100-doors-p01] The second time, only visit every 2nd door (door #2, #4, #6, ...), and toggle it.
[src:rosetta-code/100-doors-p01] The third time, visit every 3rd door (door #3, #6, #9, ...), etc, until you only visit the 100th door.
[src:rosetta-code/100-doors-p01] Answer the question: what state are the doors in after the last pass?
[src:rosetta-code/100-doors-p01] Opening only those doors is an optimization that may also be expressed; however, as should be obvious, this defeats the intent of comparing implementations across programming languages.
