[src:rosetta-code/100-doors-p01] The idea is that the *n*:th door will be flipped the same number of times as there are divisors for *n*.
[src:rosetta-code/100-doors-p01] The next step is to find the remainders of every such int when divided by every other (D∘.|D).
[src:rosetta-code/100-doors-p01] This results in a 100×100 matrix which we turn into a binary one by testing if the values are equal to zero i.e. divisors.
[src:rosetta-code/100-doors-p01] Next: sum along axis 1, i.e. the columns.
[src:rosetta-code/100-doors-p01] Finally calculate the remainder of these when divided by 2, i.e. find which *n* have an odd number of divisors, i.e. will be flipped an odd number of times and thus end up open.
[src:rosetta-code/100-doors-p01] This is similar to the above, but makes use of the fact that the final status of the first door in each pass is known as it's about to be set and the door number can thus be logged at that point if needed.
[src:rosetta-code/100-doors-p01] It makes a separate checking repeat at the end unnecessary, the toggled status boolean doesn't need to be put back into the list, and the door number can be stored in the redundant list slot instead of a separate results list having to be built.
[src:rosetta-code/100-doors-p01] It would be satisfying if the first pass, opening all the doors, could be combined with the initial creation of the doors list, but the task description does say "all initially closed"!
[src:rosetta-code/100-doors-p01] The question of which doors are flipped an odd number of times reduces to the question of which numbers in the range have an odd number of integer factors (for an AppleScript implementation of integerFactors(n) see Factors of An Integer).
[src:rosetta-code/100-doors-p01] This, on inspection, and further reflection, then collapses to the even simpler question of which numbers are perfect squares, since all other numbers have an even number of integer factors (n factors below the square root, plus n paired cofactors above the square root).
