[src:rosetta-code/100-doors-p06] The question of which doors are flipped an odd number of times reduces to the question of which numbers have an odd number of integer factors.
[src:rosetta-code/100-doors-p06] Or we can note, on inspection and further reflection, that only perfect squares have odd numbers of integer factors - all other numbers have only matched pairs of factors - low factors below the non-integer square root, and the corresponding quotients above the square root.
[src:rosetta-code/100-doors-p06] In the case of perfect squares, the additional integer square root (not paired with any other factor than itself) makes the total number of distinct factors odd.
