[src:rosetta-code/binary-search-p01] A binary search divides a range of values into halves, and continues to narrow down the field of search until the unknown value is found.
[src:rosetta-code/binary-search-p01] It is the classic example of a "divide and conquer" algorithm.
[src:rosetta-code/binary-search-p01] As an analogy, consider the children's game "guess a number." The scorer has a secret number, and will only tell the player if their guessed number is higher than, lower than, or equal to the secret number.
[src:rosetta-code/binary-search-p01] The player then uses this information to guess a new number.
[src:rosetta-code/binary-search-p01] As the player, an optimal strategy for the general case is to start by choosing the range's midpoint as the guess, and then asking whether the guess was higher, lower, or equal to the secret number.
[src:rosetta-code/binary-search-p01] If the guess was too high, one would select the point exactly between the range midpoint and the beginning of the range.
[src:rosetta-code/binary-search-p01] If the original guess was too low, one would ask about the point exactly between the range midpoint and the end of the range.
[src:rosetta-code/binary-search-p01] This process repeats until one has reached the secret number.
[src:rosetta-code/binary-search-p01] Given the starting point of a range, the ending point of a range, and the "secret value", implement a binary search through a sorted integer array for a certain number.
[src:rosetta-code/binary-search-p01] Implementations can be recursive or iterative (both if you can).
[src:rosetta-code/binary-search-p01] Print out whether or not the number was in the array afterwards.
[src:rosetta-code/binary-search-p01] There are several binary search algorithms commonly seen.
[src:rosetta-code/binary-search-p01] They differ by how they treat multiple values equal to the given value, and whether they indicate whether the element was found or not.
[src:rosetta-code/binary-search-p01] For completeness we will present pseudocode for all of them.
[src:rosetta-code/binary-search-p01] All of the following code examples use an "inclusive" upper bound (i.e.
[src:rosetta-code/binary-search-p01] Any of the examples can be converted into an equivalent example using "exclusive" upper bound (i.e.
[src:rosetta-code/binary-search-p01] The algorithms are as follows (from Wikipedia).
[src:rosetta-code/binary-search-p01] The algorithms return the index of some element that equals the given value (if there are multiple such elements, it returns some arbitrary one).
[src:rosetta-code/binary-search-p01] It is also possible, when the element is not found, to return the "insertion point" for it (the index that the value would have if it were inserted into the array).
