[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] The dining philosophers problem illustrates non-composability of low-level synchronization primitives like semaphores.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] It is a modification of a problem posed by Edsger Dijkstra.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] Five philosophers, Aristotle, Kant, Spinoza, Marx, and Russell (the tasks) spend their time thinking and eating spaghetti.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] They eat at a round table with five individual seats.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] For eating each philosopher needs two forks (the resources).
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] There are five forks on the table, one left and one right of each seat.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] When a philosopher cannot grab both forks it sits and waits.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] Eating takes random time, then the philosopher puts the forks down and leaves the dining room.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] After spending some random time thinking about the nature of the universe, he again becomes hungry, and the circle repeats itself.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] It can be observed that a straightforward solution, when forks are implemented by semaphores, is exposed to deadlock.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] There exist two deadlock states when all five philosophers are sitting at the table holding one fork each.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] One deadlock state is when each philosopher has grabbed the fork left of him, and another is when each has the fork on his right.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] There are many solutions of the problem, program at least one, and explain how the deadlock is prevented.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] The following solution uses an array of mutexes in order to model the forks.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] The forks used by a philosopher compose a subset in the array.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] When the the philosopher seizes his forks from the subset the array object prevents deadlocking since it is an atomic operation.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] In the following solution forks are implemented as plain mutexes.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] The deadlock is prevented by ordering mutexes.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] Philosopher tasks seize them in same order 1, 2, 3, 4, 5.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] Both deadlocks happen when all philosophers are in the dining room.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] The following solution has a host of the room who chatters the last philosopher while four of them are in the room.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] So there are never more than four of them in there, which prevents deadlock.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] Now the forks can be picked up in a "wrong" order, i.e. the left one first.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] AutoHotkey doesn't support concurrency, so we fake it with timers.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] Deadlock is prevented by releasing a single fork when the other is unobtainable.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] Livelock is prevented by randomly trying for the opposite fork first.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] Starvation will only occur if one (or more) of the philosophers never stops eating.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] Try changing EnoughForks to 4 and fork supply per philosopher to 2.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] This avoids deadlocks using the same strategy as the C solution (one of the philosophers picks up the left fork first).
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] Avoid deadlocks by making each philosopher have a different order of picking up forks.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] As long as one person waits for left fork first and another waits for right first, cycles can't form.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] This uses a modified version of the Python algorithm version below.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] This version uses C11 threads and the approach of making one of the philosophers left-handed to avoid deadlock.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] Aristotle is pondering about meaning of life.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] Plato is pondering about source of morality.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] Plato is pondering about how many straws makes a bale.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] Democritus is pondering about source of morality.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p01] Pythagoras is pondering about source of morality.
