[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p02] This solution for the dining philosophers is programmed in Eiffel using Simple Concurrent Object-Oriented Programming (SCOOP).
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p02] In SCOOP for Eiffel, the keyword `separate` in a declaration designates that the associated object may be handled by a SCOOP processor other than (separate from) the one handling the current object.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p02] So, in this example, philosophers and forks are all declared as separate types.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p02] The synchronization of access to the resources (the forks) occurs when the routine `eat` is called.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p02] The two arguments are the two separate forks adjacent to the philosopher.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p02] The `eat` routine will not proceed until exclusive access to all separate arguments is assured.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p02] The resources are released when the routine terminates.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p02] The example uses numbers (versus names) to identify the philosophers in order to allow the user to vary the number of philosophers.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p02] This solution avoids deadlock by employing a waiter.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p02] Deadlock prevented by making one philosopher "left-handed" and making orderly use of mutexes (mutexes protect forks by ensuring that only one philosopher can use each fork at a time).
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] Goroutine synchronization done with Go channels.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] The first solution just uses channels for synchronization.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] Channels can solve lots of problems but the sync library has a few other functions to more directly model common operations.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] In Dining Philosophers, fork use is mutually exclusive so it's very clear to model forks with sync.Mutex objects.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] Also waiting for a number of concurrent tasks to finish is a common pattern directly implemented with sync.WaitGroup.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] One more concurrency technique actually used in both solutions is to use the log package for output rather than the fmt package.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] Output from concurrent goroutines can get accidentally interleaved in some cases.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] While neither package makes claims about this problem, the log package historically has been coded to avoid interleaved output.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] Deadlocks are avoided by always getting locks on forks with lower numbers first.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] Using the built-in Software Transactional Memory in GHC.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] This Unicon solution avoids deadlock and livelock (but not starvation) by not allowing philosophers to hold onto one fork if they can't get the other, and by having each philosopher pick up their lowest numbered fork first.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] The code would be slightly simpler if the philosophers wouldn't waste time waiting when they can't get both forks and went back to thinking instead.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] A sample run, terminated after some time.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] Currently, this only works under jconsole.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] Here, to prevent deadlock, philosophers always pick up forks in a specific order and always lay down their forks in the reverse order.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] This means that one philosopher (Marx) will use the opposite left/right order from the rest of the philosophers.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] These philosophers are very smart and polite: they figured out immediately that at most two of them can eat simultaneously (take the floor of n divided by 2 for n philosophers); so, when they are hungry and it is necessary, they wait in line.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] J does not support concurrency; so, this is a discrete-event simulation (DES).
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] The time spent thinking and eating is assumed to be exponentially distributed, respectively, at the rates of 1 and 0.5 per time unit.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] This Java implementation uses a token system.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] If a philosopher's number is on the token, they pick up their left and right forks.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] Passing the token to their immediate neighbor would be pointless, so they increment the token by 2, passing it to the philosopher after their neighbor.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] The +2 works well for odd numbers of philosophers.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] With wait down at 1 millisecond I get about 1.5M eats/sec running 5 philosophers, down to about 0.5M eats/sec running 25.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] The single token generates good availability for 80% of 5 forks, but a much lower availability % of 25 forks.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] This solution allows a philosopher to take only two forks at once, or none at all.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] This is achieved by making each fork into a channel, and guarding the eating process by two forks.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] There are two channels for each philosopher: a thinking philosopher and a hungry philosopher.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] This solution is logically the same as the "minimal simple" solution above, but now the timing information is printed.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] Statistical information is also printed on hungry waiting time before eating: average among all instances of eating, and maximum time ever waited by anyone.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] This solution implements "fairness" -- if two neighbors are hungry, the one who waited more will eat first.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] The waiting time for each philosopher is bounded by twice the maximum eating time.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] Aristotle, seated on the north side, takes his left fork first since he was left-handed, see historical note in http://time.com/3107557/top-10-lefties/ and the others take the right fork first.
[src:rosetta-code/dining-philosophers-p03] The forks are represented by 5 channels.
