[src:rosetta-code/fibonacci-sequence-p01] With old computers it was common to use lookup tables to fetch pre-calculated values that would otherwise take some time to compute.
[src:rosetta-code/fibonacci-sequence-p01] The elements of the table are ordered by index, so you can simply create a function that takes an offset as the parameter and returns the element of the array at that offset.
[src:rosetta-code/fibonacci-sequence-p01] Although lookup tables are very fast, there are some drawbacks to using them.
[src:rosetta-code/fibonacci-sequence-p01] For one, you end up taking up a lot of space.
[src:rosetta-code/fibonacci-sequence-p01] We're wasting a lot of bytes to store very low numbers at the beginning (each takes up 4 bytes regardless of how many digits you see).
[src:rosetta-code/fibonacci-sequence-p01] Unfortunately, when using lookup tables you have very little choice, since trying to conditionally change the scaling of the index would more than likely take more code than encoding all data as the maximum size regardless of the contents, as was done here.
[src:rosetta-code/fibonacci-sequence-p01] This keeps it simple for the CPU, which isn't aware of the intended size of each entry of the table.
[src:rosetta-code/fibonacci-sequence-p01] For the purpose of this example, assume that both this code and the table are in the `.CODE` segment.
[src:rosetta-code/fibonacci-sequence-p01] Therefore an iterative approach has been proposed.
