[src:rosetta-code/fibonacci-sequence-p06] But what if you want the speed of the fib_acc with the recursive (more declarative) definition of fib?
[src:rosetta-code/fibonacci-sequence-p06] Then use memoization, because Mercury is a pure language fib(N, F) will always give the same F for the same N, guaranteed.
[src:rosetta-code/fibonacci-sequence-p06] We've shown the definition of fib/2 again, but the only change here is the memoization pragma (see the reference manual).
[src:rosetta-code/fibonacci-sequence-p06] This is not part of the language specification and different Mercury implementations are allowed to ignore it, however there is only one implementation so in practice memoization is fully supported.
[src:rosetta-code/fibonacci-sequence-p06] Memoization trades speed for space, a table of results is constructed and kept in memory.
[src:rosetta-code/fibonacci-sequence-p06] So this version of fib consumes more memory than than fib_acc.
[src:rosetta-code/fibonacci-sequence-p06] It is also slightly slower than fib_acc since it must manage its table of results but it is much much faster than without memoization.
[src:rosetta-code/fibonacci-sequence-p06] Memoization works very well for the Fibonacci sequence because in the naive version the same results are calculated over and over again.
