[src:rosetta-code/fizzbuzz-p03] This uses Copy (`#`) to apply a 2-integer replication vector to the boxed array `'Fizz';'Buzz'`, and then razes (`;`) the result, producing either 'Fizz', 'Buzz', or 'FizzBuzz'.
[src:rosetta-code/fizzbuzz-p03] The expression Fizz`Buzz exploits an implementation detail of Tie (`) to create two boxed strings.
[src:rosetta-code/fizzbuzz-p03] `": [^:(0=#@]) ...` conditionally replaces the result of Copy with the formatted input number if the former is empty.
[src:rosetta-code/fizzbuzz-p03] This version prepends the formatted input number to the boxed array consisting of `'Fizz';'Buzz'`, and computes a 3-integer replication vector to select from it.
[src:rosetta-code/fizzbuzz-p03] `(+:/,])@(0=3 5&|)` says to append 1 (to select the formatted number), if the input is neither divisible by 3 nor 5, or otherwise to append 0 (`+:` is NOR).
[src:rosetta-code/fizzbuzz-p03] So the replication vector ends up being `0 1 0` (selecting 'Fizz'), `0 0 1` ('Buzz'), `0 1 1` ('FizzBuzz'), or `1 0 0` (the formatted number).
[src:rosetta-code/fizzbuzz-p03] This solution uses antibase (`#.`) to decode e.g.
[src:rosetta-code/fizzbuzz-p03] `1 1` (a possible result of `5 3|]`) from base-2 into base-10, yielding e.g.
[src:rosetta-code/fizzbuzz-p03] `3`, which is used to select appropriate output from the vector of strings.
